This paper is about abstractive text summarization, which is a subfield of natural language processing (NLP) and falls under the category of computational linguistics (cs.CL). The paper proposes a regularization approach for the sequence-to-sequence model, which is a popular deep learning model used in NLP tasks. Therefore, cs.AI (artificial intelligence) and cs.LG (machine learning) are also likely sub-categories. The paper also evaluates the proposed approach using human evaluation, which involves assessing the semantic consistency of the generated summaries with the source content. This suggests that the paper may also be relevant to sub-categories such as cs.IR (information retrieval) and cs.NE (neural and evolutionary computing), which deal with tasks related to information processing and learning.
